properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Wind chill values near minus 55 are expected overnight tonight and into Friday morning. Temperatures should moderate somewhat later in the day on Friday as cloud cover increases over the region. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A vigorous frontal system will approach the South Coast on Friday morning and spread strong winds and heavy rain to the region. Southeast winds of 70 km/h will develop on Friday morning over the exposed areas of Sunshine Coast; central and northern sections of East Vancouver Island as well as the Southern Gulf Islands and Greater Victoria. The strong southeast winds will spread to the exposed areas of Metro Vancouver and southern sections of Howe Sound in the afternoon. Winds will ease and shift to northwest 40 km/h late Friday afternoon or early evening as the front passes through. ### Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard possible Friday night into Saturday. A strong low pressure system will make its way through Hudson Bay toward southern Baffin Island on Friday. Heavy snow is expected to begin late Friday or early Saturday along with rapidly intensifying easterly winds. Current indications are for up to 10 cm of fresh snow accompanied at times with winds gusting to 80 km/h. At minimum, visibility reductions in blowing snow are expected for much of Saturday. Blizzard conditions will also be possible should the system continue on its current forecast track or intensify further. Conditions will improve late Saturday as the system moves off into Foxe Basin. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Smog Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: High concentrations of fine particulates are expected and will result in a poor air quality until Friday morning. ### Smog especially affects asthmatic children and people with respiratory ailments or heart disease. It is therefore recommended that these individuals avoid intense physical activity outdoors until the smog warning is lifted. Additional information: To learn more about the Info-Smog program, go to Environment Canadas website at www.canada.ca/info-smog-program. For air quality indexes in Quebec, visit the website of the Ministre de l'Environnement et de la Lutte contre les changements climatiques at www.iqa.environnement.gouv.qc.ca/contenu/index_en.asp. For the air quality index in Montral, visit the Rseau de surveillance de la qualit de lair de la Ville de Montrals website at www.rsqa.qc.ca (french only). To learn more about the effects of smog on your health in Qubec, visit the Ministre de la Sant et des Services sociauxs website at www.quebec.ca/en/health. You can also visit the Direction rgionale de sant publique du CIUSSS du Centre-Sud-de-lle-de-Montral at www.santemontreal.qc.ca/en/public. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.

Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Blizzard beginning Friday morning and ending in the evening. A low pressure tracking across the northern Prairies will spread 10 cm of heavy snow to the Churchill area tonight. On Friday morning, strong northerly winds of 60 gusting 80 km/h will rapidly develop as the system moves into Hudson Bay. properties.Summary:
Description: An extended period of freezing drizzle is expected. Locations: northeastern Newfoundland. Time span: today, tonight, and Saturday. Remarks: Some areas, especially along the coast, will likely see a changeover to drizzle or flurries today as temperatures rise just above zero. Precipitation for all areas is forecast to change back to a mix of freezing drizzle and flurries tonight and persist through much of Saturday. Conditions are expected to improve Saturday afternoon into Saturday night as the persistent northeasterly flow weakens. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and hazardous. Freezing drizzle advisories are issued when drizzle falling in sub-zero temperatures is expected to freeze on contact, and over time create icy surfaces.
